# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ala-roman-allied-military-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] *alae*) was the term used during the middle of the Roman Republic (338–88 BC) to denote a military formation composed of conscripts from the *socii*, Rome's Italian military allies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] A normal consular army during the period consisted of two legions, composed of only Roman citizens, and two allied *alae*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] The *alae* were somewhat larger than normal legions, 5,400 or 5,100 men against the legion's 4,500 men, and it contained a greater quantity of cavalry, usually 900 horsemen against the 300 supplied by the Romans.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] From the time of the first Roman emperor, Augustus (ruled 27 BC – AD 14), the term *ala* was used in the professional imperial army to denote a much smaller (c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] 500), purely cavalry unit of the non-citizen *auxilia* corps: see ala (Roman cavalry unit).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] When the Roman armies started being composed partly of Roman citizens and partly of *socii* (allies from the rest of the Italian mainland), either Latini or Italici, it became the practice to marshal the Roman troops in the centre of the battle line and the *socii* upon the wings.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] Consular armies of the mid-Republic would consist of two legions of Roman citizens and two legions of "ala", with the ala supplying thirty turmae of cavalry per legion, whereas the Roman provided only ten turmae.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] Hence *ala* and *alarii* denoted the contingent furnished by the allies, both horse and foot, and the two divisions were distinguished as *dextera ala* (right wing) and *sinistra ala* (left wing).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-allied-military-unit] As late as Polybius' times, contingents of allies forming the alae were recruited by their own leaders in their homelands, which were expected to levy an equivalent number to the Roman troops; the specifications of those agreements were covered in the *formula togatorum*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The ***auxilia*** (Classical Latin: [au̯kˈsɪli.a], lit.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 'auxiliaries') were introduced as non-citizen troops attached to the citizen legions by Augustus after his reorganisation of the Imperial Roman army from 27 BC.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the 2nd century, the *Auxilia* contained the same number of infantry as the legions and, in addition, provided almost all of the Roman army's cavalry (especially light cavalry and archers) and more specialised troops.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The *auxilia* thus represented three-fifths of Rome's regular land forces at that time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Like their legionary counterparts, auxiliary recruits were mostly volunteers, not conscripts.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The *Auxilia* were mainly recruited from the *peregrini*, free provincial subjects who did not hold Roman citizenship and constituted the vast majority of the population in the 1st and 2nd centuries (c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In contrast to the legions, which only admitted Roman citizens, members of the *Auxilia* could be recruited from territories outside of Roman control.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Reliance on the various contingents of non-Italic troops, especially cavalry, increased when the Roman Republic employed them in increasing numbers to support its legions after 200 BC.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Julio-Claudian period (27 BC–68 AD) saw the transformation of the *Auxilia* from motley levies to a standing corps with standardised structure, equipment and conditions of service.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the end of the period, there were no significant differences between legionaries and auxiliaries in terms of training and combat capability.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Auxiliary regiments were often stationed in provinces other than that in which they were originally raised, for reasons of security and to foster the process of Romanization in the provinces.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The regimental names of many auxiliary units persisted into the 4th century, but by then the units in question were different in size, structure, and quality from their predecessors.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The mainstay of the Roman republic's war machine was the manipular legion, a heavy infantry unit suitable for close-quarter engagements on more or less any terrain, which was probably adopted sometime during the Samnite Wars (343–290 BC).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Despite its formidable strength, the legion had a number of deficiencies, especially a lack of cavalry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Around 200 BC, a legion of 4,200 infantry had a cavalry arm of only 300 horse (just 7% of the total force).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This was because the class of citizens who could afford to pay for their own horse and equipment – the equestrian order, the second rank in Roman society, after the senatorial order – was relatively small.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In addition, the legion lacked missile forces such as slingers and archers.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Until 200 BC, the bulk of a Roman army's cavalry was provided by Rome's regular Italian allies (*socii*), commonly known as the "Latin" allies, which made up the Roman military confederation.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This was Rome's defence system until the Social War of 91–88 BC.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Italian forces were organised into *alae* (literally 'wings', because they were generally posted on the flanks of the Roman line of battle).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] An allied *ala*, commanded by three Roman *praefecti sociorum*, was similar or slightly larger in infantry size (4–5,000 men) to a legion, but contained a more substantial cavalry contingent: 900 horse, three times the legionary contingent.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Since a pre-Social War consular army always contained an equal number of legions and *alae*, 75% of its cavalry was provided by the Latin allies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Roman/Latin cavalry was sufficient while Rome was in conflict with other states in the mountainous Italian peninsula, which also disposed of limited cavalry resources.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But, as Rome was confronted by external enemies that deployed far more powerful cavalry elements, such as the Gauls and the Carthaginians, the Roman deficiency in cavalry numbers could be a serious liability, which in the Second Punic War (218–202 BC) resulted in crushing defeats.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Hannibal's major victories at the Trebia and at Cannae, were owed to his Spanish and Gallic heavy cavalry, which far outnumbered the Roman and Latin levies, and to his Numidians, light, fast cavalry which the Romans wholly lacked.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The decisive Roman victory at Zama in 202 BC, which ended the war, owed much to the Numidian cavalry provided by king Massinissa, which outnumbered the Roman/Latin cavalry fielded by two to one.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] From then, Roman armies were always accompanied by large numbers of non-Italian cavalry: Numidian light cavalry and, later, Gallic heavy cavalry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] For example, Caesar relied heavily on Gallic and German cavalry for his Conquest of Gaul (58–51 BC).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] As the role of native cavalry grew, that of Roman/Latin cavalry diminished.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the early 1st century BC, Roman cavalry was phased out altogether.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] After the Social War, the *socii* were all granted Roman citizenship, the Latin **alae** abolished, and the **socii** recruited into the legions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Furthermore, Roman equestrians were no longer required to perform cavalry service after this time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The late Republican legion was thus probably bereft of cavalry (a tiny cavalry force of 120 men was probably added back to the legion under Augustus).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the outbreak of the Second Punic War, the Romans were remedying the legions' other deficiencies by using non-Italian specialised troops.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Livy reports Hiero of Syracuse offering to supply Rome with archers and slingers in 217 BC.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] From 200 BC onwards, specialist troops were hired as mercenaries on a regular basis: *sagittarii* (archers) from Crete, and *funditores* (slingers) from the Balearic Isles almost always accompanied Roman legions in campaigns all over the Mediterranean.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The other main sources of non-Italian troops in the late Republic were subject provincials, allied cities and Rome's *amici* (satellite kings).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the late Republic, non-Italian units were led by their own native chiefs, and their internal organisation was left to their own commanders.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The units varied widely in dress, equipment, and weapons.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They were normally raised for specific campaigns and often disbanded soon afterwards, in a similar manner to the earlier **socii** militia legions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] It appears that not all indigenous units were disbanded at the end of the civil war period (31 BC).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Some of the more experienced units were kept in existence to complement the legions, and became the core of the standing auxiliary forces that developed in the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the early part of Augustus' rule (27 BC onwards), the corps of regular Auxilia was created.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] It was clearly inspired by the Latin forces of the pre-Social War Republic, as a corps of non-citizen troops parallel to the legions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But there were fundamental differences, the same as between Republican and Augustan legions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Latin forces of the Republic were made up of part-time conscripts in units that would be raised and disbanded for and after particular campaigns.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Augustan Auxilia were mainly volunteer professionals serving in permanent units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The unit structure of the Auxilia also differed from the Latin **alae**, which were like legions with a larger cavalry arm.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] However, Augustus organised the Auxilia into regiments the size of cohorts (a tenth the size of legions), due to the much greater flexibility of the smaller unit size.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Further, the regiments were of three types: *ala* (cavalry), *cohors (peditata)* (infantry) and *cohors equitata* (mixed cavalry/infantry).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The evidence for the size of the Augustus' new units is not clear-cut, with our most precise evidence dating to the 2nd century, by which time the unit strengths may have changed.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] *Cohortes* were likely modelled on legionary cohorts i.e. six *centuriae* of about 80 men each (total about 480 men).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] **Alae** were divided into *turmae* (squadrons) of 30 (or 32) men, each under a *decurio* (literally: 'leader of ten').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This title derives from the old Roman cavalry of the pre-Social War republic, in which each *turma* was under the command of three *decuriones*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] *Cohortes equitatae* were infantry *cohortes* with a cavalry contingent of four *turmae* attached.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By 19 BC, the Cantabrian and Asturian Wars were concluded, leading to the annexation of northern Hispania and Lusitania.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Judging by the names of attested auxiliary regiments, these parts of the Iberian peninsula soon became a major source of recruits.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Then the Danubian regions were annexed: Raetia (annexed 15 BC), Noricum (16 BC), Pannonia (9 BC) and Moesia (6 AD), becoming, with Illyricum, the Principate's most important source of auxiliary recruits for its entire duration.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the East, where the Syrians already provided the bulk of the Roman army's archers, Augustus annexed Galatia (25 BC) and Judaea: the former, a region in central Anatolia with a Celtic-speaking people, became an important source of recruits.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Africa, Egypt, Cyrene, and Numidia (25 BC) were added to the empire.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Numidia (modern day Eastern Algeria) was home to the Numidians/Moors, the ancestors of today's Berber people.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Their light cavalry (*equites Maurorum*) was highly prized and had alternately fought and assisted the Romans for well over two centuries: they now started to be recruited into the regular Auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Even more Mauri units were formed after the annexation of Mauretania (NW Algeria, Morocco), the rest of the Berber homeland, in 44 AD by emperor Claudius (ruled 41–54).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Recruitment was thus heavy throughout the Augustan period, with a steady increase in the number of units formed.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By AD 23, the Roman historian Tacitus records that there were roughly the same numbers of auxiliaries in service as there were legionaries.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Since at this time there were 25 legions of c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 5,000 men each, the Auxilia thus amounted to c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the early Julio-Claudian period, many auxiliary regiments raised in frontier provinces were stationed in or near their home provinces, except during periods of major crises such as the Cantabrian Wars, when they were deployed temporarily in theatre.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This carried the obvious risk if their own tribe or ethnic group rebelled against Rome (or attacked the Roman frontier from outside the Empire), auxiliary troops could be tempted to make common cause with them.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Romans would then be faced by an enemy that included units fully equipped and trained by themselves, thus losing their usual tactical advantages over tribal foes.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] (This strategy was never revived by later emperors).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] At a collective level, the risk was even greater, as the hugely dangerous Illyrian revolt proved.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The central Illyrian tribes were tough and spartan shepherds of the Bosnian mountains and excellent soldier material.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Their territory formed part of the strategic province of Illyricum, recently expanded to include the territory of the Pannonii, Celticised Illyrian tribes based on the west bank of the Danube who were subjugated by Rome in 12–9 BC (the *Bellum Pannonicum*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the start of the Common Era, they were an important recruitment base for the auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But discontent was festering among the Illyrian tribes, largely due to what they saw as the rapacity of Roman tax officials.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In AD 6, several regiments of Dalmatae, a warlike Illyrian tribe, were ordered to report to a designated location to prepare to join Augustus' stepson and senior military commander Tiberius in a war against the Germans.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Instead, they mutinied at the assembly point, and defeated a Roman force sent against them.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Dalmatae were soon joined by the Breuci, another Illyrian tribe that supplied several auxiliary regiments.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They gave battle to a second Roman force from Moesia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They lost, but inflicted heavy casualties.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The rebels were now joined by a large number of other Illyrian tribes.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Dalmatae attacked the port of Salona and overran the Adriatic coast, defeating a Roman force and exposing the Roman heartland of Italy to the fear of a rebel invasion.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Augustus ordered Tiberius to break off operations in Germany and move his main army to Illyricum.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Romans had now deployed no less than 15 legions and an equivalent number of auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 150,000 men, including at least 50 auxiliary cohorts composed, exceptionally, of Roman citizens.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] These special units were accorded the title *civium Romanorum* ('of Roman citizens'), or *c.R.* for short.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] After the Illyrian revolt, these cohorts remained in being and recruited non-citizens like other auxiliary units, but retained their prestigious *c.R.* title.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In addition, the regular forces were assisted by a large number of allied troops from neighbouring Thrace deployed by their king Rhoemetalces I, a Roman *amicus* (puppet king).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Romans faced further reverses on the battlefield and a savage guerrilla war in the Bosnian mountains.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] It took them three years of hard fighting to quell the revolt, which was described by the Roman historian Suetonius, writing in c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] AD 100, as the most difficult conflict faced by Rome since the Punic Wars over two centuries earlier.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Tiberius finally succeeded in quelling the revolt in 9 AD.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This was apparently lucky timing for the Romans: that same year Arminius destroyed Varus' three legions in Germany.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Roman high command had no doubt that Arminius would have formed a grand alliance with the Illyrians.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Despite the gravity of this rebellion, the Illyrians went on, alongside their neighbours the Thracians, to become the backbone of the Roman army.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the 2nd century, with roughly half the Roman army deployed on the Danube frontier, the auxilia and legions alike were dominated by Illyrian recruits.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the 3rd century, Illyrians largely replaced Italians in the senior officer echelons of *praefecti* of auxiliary regiments and *tribuni militum* of legions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Finally, from AD 268 to 379, virtually all emperors, including Diocletian and Constantine the Great, were Romanised Illyrians from the provinces of Dalmatia, Moesia Superior and Pannonia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] These were members of a military aristocracy, outstanding soldiers who saved the empire from collapse in the turbulent late 3rd century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Significant development of the Auxilia appears to have taken place during the rule of the emperor Claudius (41–54 AD).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] A minimum term of service of 25 years was established, at the end of which the retiring auxiliary soldier, and all his children, were awarded Roman citizenship.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This is deduced from the fact that the first known Roman military diplomas date from the time of Claudius.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This was a folding bronze tablet engraved with the details of the soldier's service record, which he could use to prove his citizenship.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Claudius also decreed that prefects of auxiliary regiments must all be of equestrian rank, thus excluding centurions from such commands.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The fact that auxiliary commanders were now all of the same social rank as most *tribuni militum*, (military tribunes, a legion's senior staff officers, all of whom only one, the *tribunus laticlavius*, was of the higher senatorial rank), probably indicates that auxilia now enjoyed greater prestige.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Indigenous chiefs continued to command some auxiliary regiments, and were probably granted equestrian rank for the purpose.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] It is also likely that auxiliary pay was standardised at this time, but estimates exist only for the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Auxiliary uniform, armour, weapons and equipment were probably standardised by the end of the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Auxiliary equipment was broadly similar to that of the legions (see Section 2.1 below for possible differences in armour).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By 68 AD, there was little difference between most auxiliary infantry and their legionary counterparts in equipment, training and fighting capability.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The main difference was that auxilia contained combat cavalry, both heavy and light, and other specialized units that legions lacked.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Claudius annexed to the empire three regions that became important sources of auxiliary recruits: Britannia (43 AD), and the former client kingdoms of Mauretania (44) and Thracia (46).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The latter became as important as Illyria as a source of auxiliary recruits, especially cavalry and archers.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Britain in mid-2nd century contained the largest number of auxiliary regiments in any single province: about 60 out of about 400 (15%).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the rule of Nero (54–68), auxiliary numbers may have reached, by one estimate, about 200,000 men, implying about 400 regiments.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Batavi, a Germanic tribe, inhabited the region today known as Gelderland (Netherlands), in the Rhine river delta, then known as the *Insula Batavorum* ('Island of the Batavi', because it is surrounded by branches of the Rhine), part of the Roman province of Germania Inferior.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They were a warlike people, skilled horsemen, boatmen and swimmers.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In return for the unusual privilege of exemption from *tributum* (direct taxes on land and heads normally exacted from *peregrini*), they supplied a disproportionate number of recruits to the Julio-Claudian auxilia: one **ala** and eight *cohortes*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They also provided most of Augustus' elite personal bodyguard unit (the *Germani corpore custodes*), which continued in service until 68 AD.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Batavi auxilia amounted to about 5,000 men, implying that during the entire Julio-Claudian period, over 50% of all Batavi males reaching military age (16 years) may have enlisted in the auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Thus the Batavi, although just 0.05% of the total population of the empire of c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 70 million in 23 AD, supplied about 4% of the total auxilia i.e.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] They were regarded by the Romans as the very best (*fortissimi*, *validissimi*) of their auxiliary, and indeed all, their forces.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In Roman service, both their cavalry and infantry had perfected a technique for swimming across rivers wearing full armour and weapons.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 'Julius the Citizen', clearly a Latin name adopted on gaining Roman citizenship, not his native one) was a hereditary prince of the Batavi and the prefect of a Batavi cohort.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] A veteran of 25 years' service, he had distinguished himself by service in Britain, where he and the eight Batavi cohorts had played a crucial role in both the Roman invasion in 43 AD and the subsequent subjugation of southern Britain.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By 69, however, Civilis, the Batavi regiments and the Batavi people had become utterly disaffected with Rome.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] After the Batavi regiments were withdrawn from Britain to Italy in 66, Civilis and his brother (also a prefect) were arrested by the governor of Germania Inferior on a fabricated accusation of sedition.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The governor ordered his brother's execution, while Civilis, who as a Roman citizen had the right to appeal to the emperor, was sent to Rome in chains for judgement by Nero.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] He was released by Nero's overthrower and successor, Galba, but the latter also disbanded the imperial bodyguard unit for their loyalty to Nero.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This alienated several hundred crack Batavi troops, and indeed the whole Batavi nation who regarded it as a grave insult.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] At the same time, relations collapsed between the Batavi cohorts and the legion to which they had been attached since the invasion of Britain 25 years earlier (*XIV Gemina*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Their mutual hatred erupted in open fighting on at least two occasions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] At this juncture, the Roman empire was convulsed by its first major civil war since the Battle of Actium exactly a century earlier: the Year of the Four Emperors (69–70 AD).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The governor of Germania Inferior, ordered to raise more troops, outraged the Batavi by attempting to conscript more Batavi than the maximum stipulated in their treaty.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The brutality and corruption of the Roman recruiting-centurions (including incidents of sexual assault on Batavi young men) brought already deep discontent in the Batavi homeland to the boil.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Civilis now led his people in open revolt.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Initially, he claimed he was supporting the bid for power of Vespasian, the general in command of the legions in Syria, whom Civilis had probably befriended when both were involved in the Roman invasion of Britain 25 years earlier (Vespasian was then commander of the legion *II Augusta*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But the uprising soon became a bid for independence.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Civilis exploited the fact that some legions were absent from the Rhine area due to the civil war, and the rest under-strength.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In addition, the Roman commanders and their rank-and-file soldiers were divided by loyalty to rival emperors.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Civilis quickly won the support of the Batavi's neighbours and kinsmen, the Cananefates, who in turn won over the Frisii.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] First the rebel allies captured two Roman forts in their territory, and a cohort of Tungri defected to Civilis.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Then two legions sent against Civilis were defeated when their companion Batavi **ala** defected to his side.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The *Classis Germanica* (Rhine flotilla), largely manned by Batavi, was seized by Civilis.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Most importantly, the eight Batavi cohorts stationed at Mainz with *XIV Gemina* mutinied and joined him, defeating at Bonn a Roman force that attempted to block their return to their homeland.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By now, Civilis commanded at least 12 regiments (6,000 men) of Roman-trained and equipped auxiliary troops, as well as a much larger number of tribal levies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] A number of German tribes from beyond the Rhine joined his cause.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Several other German and Gallic units sent against him deserted, as the revolt spread to the rest of Gallia Belgica, including the Tungri, Lingones and Treviri tribes.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] He was able to destroy the two remaining legions in Germania Inferior, (*V Alaudae* and *XV Primigenia*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By this stage, Rome's entire position on the Rhine and even in Gaul was imperiled.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Their civil war over, the Romans mustered a huge task force of eight legions (five dispatched from Italy, two from Spain and one from Britain) to deal with Civilis.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Its commander Petillius Cerialis had to fight two difficult battles, at Trier and Xanten, before he could overrun the Batavi's homeland.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Tacitus' surviving narrative breaks off as he describes a meeting on an island in the Rhine delta between Civilis and Cerialis to discuss peace terms.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] We do not know the outcome of this meeting or Civilis' ultimate fate.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But, in view of his former friendship with Vespasian, who had already offered him a pardon, and the fact that the Romans still needed the Batavi levies, it is likely that the terms were lenient by Roman standards.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Petilius Cerialis took a number of reconstituted Batavi units with him to Britain, and the Batavi regiments continued to serve with special distinction in Britain and elsewhere for the rest of the 1st century and beyond.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Even as late as 395, units with the Batavi name, although long since composed of recruits from all over the empire, were still classified as elite *palatini*, e.g. the *equites Batavi seniores* (cavalry) and *auxilium Batavi seniores* (infantry).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The revolt of the Batavi appears to have led to a significant change in the Roman government's policy on deployment of Auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The revolt proved that in times of civil strife, when legions were far from their bases campaigning for rival claimants to the imperial throne, it was dangerous to leave provinces exclusively in the hands of auxiliary regiments recruited from the indigenous nation.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the Julio-Claudian period, auxiliary regiments had often been deployed away from their original home province.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But in the Flavian period (69–96), this appears to have become standard policy.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Thus in AD 70, five reconstituted Batavi regiments (one **ala** and four **cohortes**) were transferred to Britain under Petillius Cerialis, who had suppressed the Civilis revolt and then embarked on the governorship of the island.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The great majority of regiments probably founded in the 1st century were stationed away from their province of origin in the second e.g. of 13 British regiments recorded in the mid-2nd century, none were stationed in Britain.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Furthermore, it appears that in the Flavian era native noblemen were no longer permitted to command auxiliary units from their own tribe.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] After a prolonged period in a foreign province a regiment would become assimilated, since the majority of its new recruits would be drawn from the province in which it was stationed, or neighbouring provinces.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Those same "British" units, mostly based on the Danube frontier, would by c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 150, after almost a century away from their home island, be largely composed of Illyrian, Thracian and Dacian recruits.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] However, there is evidence that a few regiments at least continued to draw some recruits from their original home provinces in the 2nd century e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The Flavian period also saw the first formation of large, double-size units, both infantry and cavalry, of a nominal strength of 1,000 men (*cohors/ala milliaria*), though they were actually mostly smaller (720 for an *ala milliaria* and 800 for a *cohors milliaria*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] These were the mirror image of the double-strength first cohorts of legions also introduced at this time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Such units remained a minority of the Auxilia: in the mid-2nd century, they constituted 13% of units, containing 20% of total manpower.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In 106 AD, emperor Trajan finally defeated the Dacian kingdom of Decebalus and annexed it as the Roman province of Dacia Traiana.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the mid-2nd century, there were 44 auxiliary regiments stationed there, about 10% of the total auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Together, these two provinces contained about a quarter of the total auxiliary regiments.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] There is considerable scholarly dispute about the precise size of the auxilia during the imperial era, even during the corp's best-documented period, the rule of Trajan's successor, Hadrian (117–138).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] NOTE: Manpower figures exclude officers (centurions and decurions), which would have numbered about 3,500 men overall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In addition, Holder believes that a further 14 **cohortes**, which are attested under Trajan, immediately before Hadrian's rule, but not during or after it, probably continued in existence, giving a total of 381 units and 225,000 effectives.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The discrepancy between the two scholars is due to: (i) Interpretation of units with the same name and number, but attested in different provinces in the same period.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Spaul tends to take a more cautious approach and to assume such are the same unit moving base frequently, while Holder tends to regard them as separate units which acquired the same number due to duplicated (or even triplicated) seriation.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] (ii) Assumptions about how many **cohortes** were **equitatae**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Spaul accepts only those **cohortes** specifically attested as **equitatae** i.e., about 40% of recorded units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Holder estimates that at least 70% of **cohortes** contained cavalry contingents by the early 2nd century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Even according to the more conservative estimate, the auxilia were by this time significantly larger than the legions, which contained c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 155,000 effectives (28 legions of 5,500 men each) at this time, of which just 3,360 were cavalry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] (For a detailed breakdown, see section 4: Auxilia deployment in the 2nd century, below).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the second half of the 2nd century, the Roman army underwent considerable further expansion, with the addition of five new legions (27,500 men) to a Principate peak of 33.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 50 regiments, although only the names of around 25–30 have survived in the epigraphic record) were probably added, possibly reaching a peak of c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] 440 regiments and around 250,000 effectives by the end of Septimius Severus's rule (211 AD).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] During the 2nd century, some units with the new names *numerus* ('group') and *vexillatio* ('detachment') appear in the diploma record.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Their size is uncertain, but was likely smaller than the regular *alae* and **cohortes**, as originally they were probably detachments from the latter, acquiring independent status after long-term separation.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] As these units are mentioned in diplomas, they were presumably part of the regular auxiliary organisation.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But *numeri* was also a generic term used for barbarian units outside the regular auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] (see section 2.4 Irregular units, below).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In 212, the *constitutio Antoniniana* (Antonine decree) of emperor Caracalla granted Roman citizenship to all the free inhabitants of the Empire – the **peregrini** – thus abolishing their second-class status.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But there is no evidence that the citizens-only rule for legions was also abolished at this time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The legions simply gained a much wider recruitment base, as they were now able to recruit any male free resident of the empire.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] Auxiliary units were now recruited mainly from Roman citizens, but probably continued to recruit non-citizen *barbari* from outside the Empire's borders.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] However, the citizens-only rule for legions appears to have been dropped some time during the 3rd century, as by the 4th-century Romans and barbarians are found serving together in all units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the mid to late 3rd century, the army was afflicted by a combination of military disasters and of pestilence, the so-called Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In 251–271, Gaul, the Alpine regions and Italy, the Balkans and the East were simultaneously overrun by Alamanni, Sarmatians, Goths and Persians respectively.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] At the same time, the Roman army was struggling with the effects of a devastating pandemic, probably of smallpox: the Plague of Cyprian, which began in 251 and was still raging in 270, when it claimed the life of emperor Claudius II Gothicus.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The evidence for an earlier pandemic, the Antonine Plague (also smallpox) indicates a mortality of 15–30% in the empire as a whole.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The armies would likely have suffered deaths at the top end of the range, due to their close concentration of individuals and frequent movements across the empire.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This probably led to a steep decline in military numbers, which only recovered at the end of the century under Diocletian (r.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The recruitment shortfall caused by the crisis seems to have led to recruitment of barbarians to the auxilia on a much greater scale than previously.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] By the 4th century, it has been estimated that some 25% of regular army recruits were barbarian-born.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the elite *palatini* regiments, anywhere between a third and a half of recruits may have been barbarian.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This is likely a much greater proportion of foreigners than joined the auxilia in the 1st and 2nd centuries.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the 3rd century, a small number of regular auxiliary units appear in the record that, for the first time, bear the names of barbarian tribes from outside the empire e.g. the *ala I Sarmatarum* attested in 3rd-century Britain.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This was probably an offshoot of the 5,500 surrendered Sarmatian horsemen posted on Hadrian's Wall by emperor Marcus Aurelius in c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This unit may be an early example of a novel process whereby irregular units of **barbari** (*foederati*) were transformed into regular auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] This process intensified in the 4th century: the **Notitia Dignitatum**, a key document on the late Roman army, lists a large number of regular units with barbarian names.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the 4th century, the Roman army underwent a radical restructuring.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In the rule of Diocletian (284–305), the traditional Principate formations of *legiones*, **alae** and **cohortes** appear to have been broken up into smaller units, many of which bore a variety of new names.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The old Principate auxilia regiments provided the basis for units at all three grades.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The *Notitia Dignitatum* lists about 70 **alae** and **cohortes** that retained their 2nd-century names, mostly *limitanei*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But traces of other auxilia regiments can be found in the *praesentales* and *comitatenses* armies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] For example, many of the new-style *auxilia palatina* infantry regiments, considered among the best units in the army, were probably formed from old-style auxiliary **cohortes**, which they appear to closely resemble.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] The late 4th-century writer on military affairs Vegetius complains of contemporary young men joining the "auxilia" in preference to the "legions" to avoid the latter's tougher training and duties.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] But it is unclear what types of units he was referring to.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] It is possible that those older terms were still popularly used (misleadingly) to mean **limitanei** and *comitatenses* respectively.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p01] In any event, his quote in no way describes accurately the Principate auxilia, many of which were of very high quality.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The following table sets out the official, or establishment, strength of auxiliary units in the 2nd century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The real strength of a unit would fluctuate continually, but would likely have been somewhat less than the establishment most of the time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] NOTE: Opinion is divided about the size of an *ala turma*, between 30 and 32 men.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] 30 was the size of a *turma* in the Republican cavalry and in the *cohors equitata* of the Principate auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Against this is a statement by Arrian that an **ala** was 512 strong.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This would make an *ala turma* 32 men strong.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These all-infantry units were modeled on the cohorts of the legions, with the same officers and sub-units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were typically considered to be more of a light infantry than proper legionaries.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Some auxiliaries may however have been equipped with the *lorica segmentata*, the most sophisticated legionary body armour, although scholars dispute this.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Besides this possibility, monuments (like on Trajan's Column) show auxiliaries wearing chain-mail armor, the length and form of which varied over the first and second century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They wore helmets similar to those of the Legion.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Yet they seem to be simplified versions that were further improved over the same timeframe.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were equipped with a sword, a dagger and one or more spears or javelins.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This spear might have been a *lancea*, which can be used as a javelin as well as a thrusting spear.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Based on archeological evidences auxiliaries probably had additional lighter javelins to their *lancea*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliary infantry fought in a looser order than legionaries.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It appears that in a set-piece battle line, auxiliary infantry would normally be stationed on the flanks, with legionary infantry holding the centre e.g. as in the Battle of Watling Street (AD 60), the final defeat of the rebel Britons under queen Boudicca.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This was a tradition inherited from the Republic, when the precursors of auxiliary **cohortes**, the Latin **alae**, occupied the same position in the line.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The flanks of the line required equal, if not greater, skill to hold as the centre.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] During the Principate period of the Roman Empire (30 BC – AD 284), the all-mounted **Alae** ('wings') contained the elite cavalry of the army.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were specially trained in elaborate manoeuvres, such as those displayed to the emperor Hadrian during a documented inspection in Numidia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were best-suited for large-scale operations and battle, during which they acted as the primary cavalry escort for the legions, which had almost no cavalry of their own.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Roman *alares* were normally armoured, with mail or scale body armour, a cavalry version of the infantry helmet (with more protective features, such as completely covered ears) and oval shield or hexagonal.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Their weapons could be a lance, javelins, or bow and arrow but all Roman horseman had a sword (called a *spatha*) and a dagger (the *pugio*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The elite status of an *alaris* is shown by the fact that he received 20% more pay than his counterpart in an auxiliary cohort or a legionary infantryman.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The favored sources of recruitment for the cavalry of the *auxilia* were Gauls, Germans, Iberians and Thracians.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] All of these peoples had long-established skills and experience of fighting from horseback – in contrast to the Romans themselves.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The **alae** were better paid and mounted than the more numerous horsemen of the *cohortes equitatae* (see below).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These were **cohortes** with a cavalry contingent attached.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There is evidence that their numbers expanded with the passage of time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Only about 40% of attested **cohortes** are specifically attested as *equitatae* in inscriptions, which is probably the original Augustan proportion.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A study of units stationed in Syria in the mid-2nd century found that many units that did not carry the *equitata* title did in fact contain cavalrymen e.g. by discovery of a tombstone of a cavalryman attached to the cohort.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This implies that by that time, at least 70% of **cohortes** were probably **equitatae**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The addition of cavalry to a cohort obviously enabled it to carry out a wider range of independent operations.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A *cohors equitata* was in effect a self-contained mini-army.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The traditional view of *equites cohortales* (the cavalry arm of **cohortes equitatae**), as expounded by G.L.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Cheesman, was that they were just a mounted infantry with poor-quality horses.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They would use their mounts simply to reach the battlefield and then would dismount to fight.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Although it is clear that **equites cohortales** did not match *equites alares* (*ala* cavalrymen) in quality (hence their lower pay), the evidence is that they fought as cavalry in the same way as the **alares** and often alongside them.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Their armour and weapons were the same as for the *alares*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Nevertheless, non-combat roles of the **equites cohortales** differed significantly from the **alares**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Non-combat roles such as despatch riders (*dispositi*) were generally filled by cohort cavalry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the Republican period, the standard trio of specialised auxilia were Balearic slingers, Cretan archers and Numidian light cavalry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These functions, plus some new ones, continued in the 2nd-century auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were known as the *equites Maurorum* or *Numidarum* ('Moorish or Numidian cavalry').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] On Trajan's Column, Mauri horsemen, depicted with long hair in dreadlocks, are shown riding their small but resilient horses bare-back and unbridled, with a simple braided rope round their mount's neck for control.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They wear no body or head armour, carrying only a small, round leather shield.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Their weaponry cannot be discerned due to stone erosion, but is known from Livy to have consisted of several short javelins.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Exceptionally fast and maneuverable, Numidian cavalry would harass the enemy by hit-and-run attacks, riding up and loosing volleys of javelins, then scattering faster than any opposing cavalry could pursue.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were superbly suited to scouting, harassment, ambush and pursuit.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It is unclear what proportion of the Numidian cavalry were regular auxilia units as opposed to irregular **foederati** units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the 3rd century, new formations of light cavalry appear, apparently recruited from the Danubian provinces: the *equites Dalmatae* ('Dalmatian cavalry').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Little is known about these, but they were prominent in the 4th century, with several units listed in the *Notitia Dignitatum*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A unit of *dromedarii* ('camel-mounted troops') is attested from the 2nd century, the *ala I Ulpia dromedariorum milliaria* in Syria.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A substantial number of auxiliary regiments (32, or about 1 in 12 in the 2nd century) were denoted *sagittariorum*, or archer-units (from *[[sagittarii|*sagittarii*]]* lit.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These 32 units (of which four were double-strength) had a total official strength of 17,600 men.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] All three types of auxiliary regiment (**ala**, *cohors* and *cohors equitata*) could be denoted *sagittariorum*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Although these units evidently specialised in archery, it is uncertain from the available evidence whether all **sagittariorum** personnel were archers, or simply a higher proportion than in ordinary units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] At the same time, ordinary regiments probably also possessed some archers, otherwise their capacity for independent operations would have been unduly constrained.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Bas reliefs appear to show personnel in ordinary units employing bows.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] From about 218 BC onwards, the archers of the Roman army of the mid-Republic were virtually all mercenaries from the island of Crete, which boasted a long specialist tradition.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] During the late Republic (88–30 BC) and the Augustan period, Crete was gradually eclipsed by men from other, much more populous, regions subjugated by the Romans with strong archery traditions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These included Thrace, Anatolia and, above all, Syria.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Of the 32 *sagittarii* units attested in the mid-2nd century, thirteen have Syrian names, seven Thracian, five from Anatolia, one from Crete and the remaining six of other or uncertain origin.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Three distinct types of archers are shown on Trajan's Column: (a) with scalar cuirass, conical steel helmet and cloak; (b) without armour, with cloth conical cap and long tunic; or (c) equipped in the same way as general auxiliary foot-soldiers (apart from carrying bows instead of javelins).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The first type were probably Syrian or Anatolian units; the third type probably Thracian.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The standard bow used by Roman auxilia was the recurved composite bow, a sophisticated, compact and powerful weapon.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] From about 218 BC onwards, the Republican army's slingers were exclusively mercenaries from the Balearic Islands, which had nurtured a strong indigenous tradition of slinging from prehistoric times.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] As a result, in classical Latin, *Baleares* (literally 'inhabitants of the Balearic Islands') became an alternative word for 'slingers' (*funditores*, from *funda* 'sling').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Because of this, it is uncertain whether most of the imperial army's slingers continued to be drawn from the Balearics themselves, or, like archers, derived mainly from other regions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Independent slinger units are not attested in the epigraphic record of the Principate.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, slingers are portrayed on Trajan's Column.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They are shown unarmoured, wearing a short tunic.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They carry a cloth bag, slung in front, to hold their shot (*glandes*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Throughout the Principate period, there is evidence of ethnic units of *barbari* outside the normal auxilia organisation fighting alongside Roman troops.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] To an extent, these units were simply a continuation of the old client-king levies of the late Republic: ad hoc bodies of troops supplied by Rome's puppet petty-kings on the imperial borders for particular campaigns.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Some clearly remained in Roman service beyond the campaigns, keeping their own native leadership, attire and equipment and structure.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These units were known to the Romans as *socii* ('allies'), *symmachiarii* (from *symmachoi*, Greek for 'allies') or *foederati* ('treaty troops' from *foedus*, 'treaty').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] One estimate puts the number of *foederati* in the time of Trajan at about 11,000, divided into about 40 **numeri** (units) of about 300 men each.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The purpose of employing **foederati** units was to use their specialist fighting skills.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Many of these would have been troops of Numidian cavalry (see light cavalry above).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The **foederati** make their first official appearance on Trajan's Column, where they are portrayed in a standardised manner, with long hair and beards, barefoot, stripped to the waist, wearing long trousers held up by wide belts and wielding clubs.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In reality, several different tribes supported the Romans in the Dacian wars.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Their attire and weapons would have varied widely.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The Column stereotypes them with the appearance of a single tribe, probably the most outlandish-looking, to differentiate them clearly from the regular auxilia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Judging by the frequency of their appearance in the Column's battle scenes, the **foederati** were important contributors to the Roman operations in Dacia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Another example of **foederati** are the 5,500 captured Sarmatian cavalrymen sent by Emperor Marcus Aurelius (r.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] 161–180) to garrison a fort on Hadrian's Wall after their defeat in the Marcomannic Wars.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The evidence for auxiliary ranks and pay is scant: even less exists than the patchy evidence for their legionary counterparts.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There seems to be some consensus, however, that the auxiliary was paid one third of what a legionary received: 300 sesterces a year (400 after the reign of the emperor Commodus).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Both auxiliaries and seamen received the *viaticum* of 300 sesterces, although the various sources differ as to whether auxiliaries and sailors received the retirement bonus known as the *honesta missio*, or honorable discharge.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] At the bottom end of the rank pyramid, rankers were known as *caligati* (lit.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] 'sandal men' from the *caligae* or hob-nailed sandals worn by soldiers).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Depending on the type of regiment they belonged to, they held the official ranks of *pedes* (foot soldier in a *cohors*), *eques* (cavalryman in a *cohors equitata*) and *gregalis* (*ala* cavalryman).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] During the Principate, recruitment into the legions was restricted to Roman citizens only.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This rule, which derived from the pre-Social War Republican army, was strictly enforced.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The few exceptions recorded, such as during emergencies and for the illegitimate sons of legionaries, do not warrant the suggestion that the rule was routinely ignored.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the 1st century, the vast majority of auxiliary common soldiers were recruited from the Roman *peregrini* (second-class citizens).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the Julio-Claudian era, conscription of *peregrini* seems to have been practiced alongside voluntary recruitment, probably in the form of a fixed proportion of men reaching military age in each tribe being drafted.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] From the Flavian era onwards, the auxilia were an all-volunteer force.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Although recruits as young as 14 are recorded, the majority of recruits (66%) were from the 18–23 age group.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] When it was first raised, an auxiliary regiment would have been recruited from the native tribe or people whose name it bore.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the early Julio-Claudian period, it seems that efforts were made to preserve the ethnic integrity of units, even when the regiment was posted in a faraway province.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] But in the later part of the period, recruitment in the region where the regiment was posted increased and became predominant from the Flavian era onwards.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The regiment would thus lose its original ethnic identity.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The unit's name would thus become a mere curiosity devoid of meaning, although some of its members might inherit foreign names from their veteran ancestors.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This view has to be qualified, however, as evidence from military diplomas and other inscriptions shows that some units continued to recruit in their original home areas e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Batavi units stationed in Britain, where some units had an international membership.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It also appears that the Danubian provinces (Raetia, Pannonia, Moesia, Dacia) remained key recruiting grounds for units stationed all over the empire.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Researchers have often assumed that Roman citizens were also regularly recruited to the auxilia because various sources record auxiliary soldiers with the Tria nomina.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Explanations for that phenomenon include that sons of auxiliary veterans preferred to join their fathers' old regiments, which were a kind of extended family to them, rather than join a much larger, unfamiliar legion.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, it has been shown that many of the auxiliary soldiers with tria nomina were not full Roman citizens that could enter a legion, but only had Latin citizenship or belonged (as sons of freedmen) to the "Latini Iuniani".
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There are, however, also instances of legionaries transferring to the auxilia (to a higher rank).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] After the grant of citizenship to all **peregrini** in 212, auxiliary regiments became predominantly citizen units.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Less clearcut is the question of whether the regular auxilia recruited *barbari* (barbarians, as the Romans called people living outside the empire's borders).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Although there is little evidence of it before the 3rd century, the consensus is that auxilia recruited barbarians throughout their history.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the 3rd century, a few auxilia units of clearly barbarian origin start to appear in the record e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *Ala I Sarmatarum*, *cuneus Frisiorum* and *numerus Hnaufridi* in Britain.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There existed a hierarchy of pay between types of auxiliary, with cavalry higher paid than infantry.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] One recent estimate is that in the time of Augustus, the annual pay structure was: *eques alaris* (*gregalis*) 263 *denarii*, *eques cohortalis* 225, and *cohors* infantryman 188.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The same differentials (of about 20% between grades) seem to have existed at the time of Domitian (r.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, Goldsworthy points out that the common assumption that rates of pay were universal across provinces and units is unproven.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Pay may have varied according to the origin of the unit.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Gross salary was subject to deductions for food, clothing, boots and hay (probably for the company mules).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It is unclear whether the cost of armour and weapons was also deducted, or borne by the army.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Deductions left the soldier with a net salary of 78 **denarii**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This sum was sufficient, on the basis of the food deduction, to amply feed an adult for a year.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In 84 AD Domitian increased basic legionary pay by 33% (from 225 to 300 **denarii**): a similar increase was presumably accorded to auxiliaries, boosting their net income to 140 **denarii**, i.e. more than two food allowances.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It was entirely disposable, as the soldier was exempt from the poll tax (*capitatio*), did not pay rent (he was housed in fort barracks) and his food, clothing and equipment were already deducted.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It should be borne in mind that most recruits came from peasant families living at subsistence level.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] To such persons, any disposable income would appear attractive.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It could be spent on leisure activities, sent to relatives or simply saved for retirement.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliaries received the substantial cash bonuses (donativum) handed to legionaries on the accession of a new emperor and other occasions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Although irregular, these payments (each worth 75 **denarii** to a common legionary) averaged once every 7.5 years in the early 1st century and every three years later.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Duncan-Jones has suggested that *donativa* may have been paid to auxiliaries also from the time of Hadrian onwards, on the grounds that the total amount of donative to the military increased sharply at that time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A very valuable benefit paid to legionaries was the discharge bonus (*praemia*) paid on completion of the full 25 years' service.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] At 3,000 **denarii**, this was equivalent to ten years' gross salary for a common legionary after the pay increase of 84 AD.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] It would enable him to purchase a substantial plot of land.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Again, there is no indication that auxiliaries were paid a discharge bonus.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] For auxiliaries, the discharge bonus was the grant of Roman citizenship, which carried important tax exemptions.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, Duncan-Jones argues that the fact that service in the auxilia was competitive with the legions (deduced from the many Roman citizens that joined the auxilia) that a discharge bonus may have been paid.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Below centurion/decurion rank, junior officers in the Roman army were known as *principales*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] An auxiliary cohort's ranks appear the same as in a legionary *centuria*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These were, in ascending order: *tesserarius* ('officer of the watch'), *signifer* (standard-bearer for the *centuria*), *optio* (centurion's deputy) and *vexillarius* (standard-bearer for the whole regiment, from *vexillum*).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the *turmae* of **cohortes equitatae** (and of **alae**?), the decurion's second-in-command was probably known as a *curator*, responsible for horses and caparison.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] As in the legions, the *principales*, together with some regimental specialists, were classified in two pay-scales: *sesquiplicarii* ('one-and-a-half-pay men') and *duplicarii* ('double-pay men').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] These ranks are probably most closely resembled by the modern ranks of corporal and sergeant respectively.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Besides combat effectives, regiments also contained specialists, the most senior of whom were *sesquiplicarii* or *duplicarii*, the rest common soldiers with the status of *milities immunes* ('exempt soldiers' i.e. exempt from normal duties).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Ranking specialists included the *medicus* (regimental doctor), *veterinarius* (veterinary doctor, in charge of the care of horses, pack animals and livestock), *custos armorum* (keeper of the armoury), and the *cornicularius* (clerk in charge of all the regiment's records and paperwork).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The limited evidence on auxiliary **centuriones** and *decuriones* is that such officers could be directly commissioned as well as promoted from the ranks.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Many appear to have come from provincial aristocracies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Those rising from the ranks could be promotions from the legions as well as from the regiment's own ranks.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the Julio-Claudian period auxiliary *centuriones* and **decuriones** were a roughly equal split between citizens and **peregrini**, though later citizens became predominant due to the spread of citizenship among military families.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Because **centuriones** and **decuriones** often rose from the ranks, they have often been compared to warrant officers such as sergeants major in modern armies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, centurions' social role was much wider than a modern warrant officer.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In addition to their military duties, centurions performed a wide range of administrative tasks, which was necessary in the absence of an adequate bureaucracy to support provincial governors.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] They were also relatively wealthy, due to their high salaries (see table above).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] However, most of the surviving evidence concerns legionary centurions and it is uncertain whether their auxiliary counterparts shared their high status and non-military role.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There is little evidence about the pay-scales of auxiliary **centuriones** and **decuriones**, but these are also believed to have amounted to several times that of a *miles*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Unlike a *legatus legionis* (who had an officer staff of six *tribuni militum* and one *praefectus castrorum*), an auxiliary **praefectus** does not appear to have enjoyed the support of purely staff officers.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The possible exception is an attested *beneficiarius* ('deputy'), who may have been the *praefectus*' second-in-command, if this title was a regular rank and not simply an ad hoc appointment for a specific task.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Also attached to the **praefectus** were the regiment's *vexillarius* (standard-bearer for the whole unit) and *cornucen* (horn-blower).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] From a survey by Devijver of persons whose origin can be determined, it appears that during the 1st century, the large majority (65%) of auxiliary prefects were of Italian origin.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The Italian proportion dropped steadily, to 38% in the 2nd century, and 21% in the 3rd century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] 41–54) only Roman knights were eligible to hold command of an auxiliary regiment.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Equestrians by birth would normally begin their military careers at c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] An axillary had to do 25 years of service before joining the army.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Commands were held in a set sequence, each held for 3–4 years: prefect of an auxiliary **cohors**, **tribunus militum** in a legion and finally prefect of an auxiliary **ala**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In Hadrian's time, a fourth command was added, for exceptionally able officers, of prefect of an *ala milliaria*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Like officers senatorial rank, hereditary equestrians held civilian posts before and after their decade of military service, whereas non-hereditary officers tended to remain in the army, commanding various units in various provinces.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] By the 3rd century, most auxiliary prefects had exclusively military careers.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The pay of a **praefectus** of an auxiliary regiment in the early 2nd century has been estimated at over 50 times that of a *miles* (common soldier).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] (This compares to a full colonel in the British Army, who is currently paid about five times a private's salary).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The reason for the huge gap between the top and the bottom of the pyramid is that Roman society was far more hierarchical than a modern one.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A **praefectus** was not just a senior officer.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] He was also a Roman citizen (which most of his men were not) and, as a member of the equestrian order, an aristocrat.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The social gulf between the **praefectus** and a *peregrinus* soldier was thus immense, and the pay differential reflected that fact.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The nomenclature of the great majority of regiments followed a standard configuration: unit type, followed by serial number, followed by name of the **peregrini** tribe (or nation) from whom the regiment was originally raised, in the genitive plural case e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *cohors III Batavorum* ('3rd Cohort of Batavi'); *cohors I Brittonum* ('1st Cohort of Britons').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Some regiments combine the names of two **peregrini** tribes, most likely after the merger of two previously separate regiments e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *ala I Pannoniorum et Gallorum* ('1st Wing of Pannonii and Gauls').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] A minority of regiments are named after an individual, mostly after the first prefect of the regiment, e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *ala Sulpicia* (presumably named after a prefect whose middle (*gens*) name was Sulpicius).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The latter is also an example of a regiment that did not have a serial number.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Regiments were often rewarded for meritorious service by the grant of an honorific title.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The most sought-after was the prestigious *c.R.* (*civium Romanorum* 'of Roman citizens') title.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] In the latter case, all the regiment's members at the time, but not their successors, would be granted Roman citizenship.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] But the regiment would retain the *c.R*. title in perpetuity.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Another common title was the *gens* name of the emperor making the award (or founding the regiment) e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *Ulpia*: the **gens** name of Trajan (Marcus Ulpius Traianus r.98–117).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Other titles were similar to those given to the legions e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *pia fidelis* (*p.f.* 'dutiful and loyal').
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The Roman army awarded a variety of individual decorations (*dona*) for valour to its legionaries.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *Hasta pura* was a miniature spear; *phalerae* were large medal-like bronze or silver discs worn on the cuirass; *armillae* were bracelets worn on the wrist; and torques were worn round the neck, or on the cuirass.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The highest awards were the *coronae* ('crowns'), of which the most prestigious was the *corona civica*, a crown made of oak leaves awarded for saving the life of a Roman citizen in battle.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The most valuable award was the *corona muralis*, a crown made of gold awarded to the first man to scale an enemy rampart.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] This was awarded rarely, as such a man hardly ever survived.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliary common soldiers received individual decorations, although auxiliary officers did.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Instead, the whole regiment was honoured by a title reflecting the type of award e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *torquata* (awarded a torque) or *armillata* (awarded bracelets).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Some regiments would, in the course of time, accumulate a long list of titles and decorations e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] *cohors I Brittonum Ulpia torquata pia fidelis c.R.*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Notes: (1) Table excludes about 2,000 officers (centurions and above).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The table shows that legions did not have a standard complement of auxiliary regiments and that there was no fixed ratio of auxiliary regiments to legions in each province.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The ratio varied from six regiments per legion in Cappadocia to 40 per legion in Mauretania.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Overall, cavalry represented about 20% (including the small contingents of legionary cavalry) of the total army effectives.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] But there were variations: in Mauretania the cavalry proportion was 28%.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] The figures show the massive deployments in Britannia and Dacia.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ala-roman-cavalry-unit-p02] Together, these two provinces account for 27% of the total auxilia corps.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alb-limes] The **Alb Limes** (German: *Alblimes*) is a Roman frontier fortification or *limes* of the late 1st century AD in the Swabian Jura, also known as the Swabian Alb.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alb-limes] The Alb Limes runs for just under 135 kilometres from Rottweil (Latin: *Arae Flaviae*) in the southwest to Heidenheim an der Brenz (Latin: *Aquileia*), Germany, in the northeast.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] An **alliance** is a relationship among people, groups, or states that have joined together for mutual benefit or to achieve some common purpose, whether an explicit agreement has been worked out among them.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Members of an alliance are called **allies**.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Alliances form in many settings, including political alliances, military alliances, and business alliances.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] When spelled with a capital "A", "the Allies" usually denotes the countries who fought together against the Central Powers in World War I (the Allies of World War I), or those who fought against the Axis Powers in World War II (the Allies of World War II).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] In the second half of the 20th century, the Cold War was characterised by the intense rivalry between the military alliances of NATO and the Warsaw Pact, as each competed to expand and maintain their spheres of influence.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] More recently, the term "Allied forces" has also been used to describe the coalition of the Gulf War, as opposed to forces the Multi-National Forces in Iraq which are commonly referred to as "Coalition forces" or, as by the George W.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Bush administration, "the coalition of the willing".
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] At the onset of the 21st century, shifts in the global order led to the formation of new alliances rooted in ideological and historical precedents, exemplified by Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa (BRICS).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] This alliance possesses a broad and vaguely defined agenda, with its members exhibiting varying degrees of commitment to and motivations for participating in this initiative.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] The inaugural BRICS meeting occurred in 2006.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] In 2023, the alliance expanded with the invitation of six new members—Argentina, Egypt, Ethiopia, Iran, Saudi Arabia, and the United Arab Emirates—and was rebranded as BRICS Plus.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Scholars are divided as to the impact of alliances.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Several studies find that defensive alliances deter conflict.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] One study questions these findings, showing that alliance commitments deterred conflict in the prenuclear era but has no statistically meaningful impact on war in the postnuclear era.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Another study finds that while alliance commitments deter conflict between sides with a recent history of conflict, alliances tend to provoke conflicts between states without such a history.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] A 2000 study in the *Journal of Conflict Resolution* found that allies fulfill their alliance commitments approximately 75% of the time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Most research suggests that democracies are more reliable allies than non-democracies.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] A 2004 study did however question whether alliance commitments by democracies are more durable.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] A 2018 study updated and extended the data from the 2000 *Journal of Conflict Resolution* study and found that allies only fulfill their commitments about 50% of the time from 1816 to 2003.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] According to the study, "States honored their alliance commitments 66% of the time prior to 1945 but the compliance rate drops to 22% from 1945 to 2003.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] One of the most profound effects of alliances can be seen in technological innovation, due to conduits of knowledge flows that are open between allies but closed between rivals.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] According to a 2017 poll by WIN/GIA, the United States was the most preferred ally internationally.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Russia, Iran, North Korea, and China (CRINK), who preferred one another, both trailed America globally.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Four countries, Bulgaria, Greece, Slovenia and Turkey, preferred Russia, despite being members of NATO.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] In Pakistan, 72% of respondents preferred ties to China, the largest margin of any country surveyed, while 46% of Bangladesh preferred India.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] A total of 22 countries indicated a preference for the United Kingdom at a rate of 10% or more, but the United States was the only country to prefer Britain over any other, at a rate of 43%.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Five countries preferred France at a rate of 10% or more, led by Belgium at a rate of 25%.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] A single country, Iraq, expressed no preference, while three other countries, Lebanon, Palestine, and Slovenia, expressed no preference at a rate of 11% or more, although at a smaller rate than their preference for Russia on the part of Lebanon and Slovenia, and China on the part of Palestine.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] Kosovo reported the most unified opinion, preferring the United States at a rate of 92%, while Russia's most unified supporters were Mongolia (71%), Armenia (67%) and Serbia (56%).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/alliance] In total, 21 countries expressed a preference for America at a rate of 50% or more.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] Originally some 56 km (35 mi) long, it stretches from Evcik İskelesi in Çatalca at the Black Sea coast across the Thracian peninsula to the coast of the Sea of Marmara at 6 km (3.7 mi) west of Silivri (ancient Selymbria).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] It ran from north to south through the locations what are today Karacaköy, Gümüşpınar, Pınarca, Kurfallı, Fener, Alipaşa Neighborhood and Silivri Altınorak.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] Remains of the wall are visible in Gümüşpınar junction in Karacaköy, Hisartepe in Yalıköy, Pınarca in İhsaniye and Kurfallı village.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] The wall was part of an additional outer defense system for Constantinople, capital of the Eastern Roman Empire and probably continued in use until the 7th century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] The wall was named after the Emperor Anastasius I (r.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] However, there is evidence that the fortification already existed in 469 during the reign of Leo I (r.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] 476–491), and it was maintained and renewed by Anastasius in the time from 507 to 512.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] The wall had a thickness of 3.3 m (11 ft) and a height over 5 m (16 ft).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] It was built complete with towers, gates, forts, ditches and a military way to protect Constantinople from invasions from the west by Huns, Slavs and Bulgars.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] A rectangular *castrum* with dimensions of 250 m (820 ft) by 300 m (980 ft) existed also in the central section of the wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] The wall fell into ruin after it was abandoned in the 7th century because of the difficulty of keeping it manned and repaired.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] Over the centuries, the stone of more than half of the total length was reused in other local buildings.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/anastasian-wall] It is best preserved in the woodlands of the northern sector.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Defensive walls are a feature of ancient Roman architecture.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans generally fortified cities, rather than building stand-alone fortresses, but there are some fortified camps, such as the Saxon Shore forts like Porchester Castle in England.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] City walls were already significant in Etruscan architecture, and in the struggle for control of Italy under the early Republic many more were built, using different techniques.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] These included tightly fitting massive irregular polygonal blocks, shaped to fit exactly in a way reminiscent of later Inca work.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans called a simple rampart wall an agger; at this date great height was not necessary.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Servian Wall around Rome was an ambitious project of the early 4th century BC.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The wall was up to 10 metres (32.8 ft) in height in places, 3.6 metres (12 ft) wide at its base, 11 km (7 mi) long, and is believed to have had 16 main gates, though many of these are mentioned only from writings, with no other known remains.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Some of it had a *fossa* or ditch in front, and an agger behind, and it was enough to deter Hannibal.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Later the Aurelian Wall replaced it, enclosing an expanded city, and using more sophisticated designs, with small forts at intervals.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans walled major cities and towns in areas they saw as vulnerable, and parts of many walls remain incorporated in later defences, as at Córdoba (2nd century BC), Chester (earth and wood in the 70s AD, stone from c.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Strategic walls defending the frontiers of the Empire by running across open country were far rarer, and Hadrian's Wall (from 122) and the Antonine Wall (from 142, abandoned only 8 years after completion) are the most significant examples, both on the Pictish frontier.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Most defences of the borders of the Roman Empire relied on systems of forts and roads without attempting a continuous barrier.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/ann-hyland] Ann Hyland trains horses as well as being a freelance lecturer on equestrian topics.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The **Antonine Wall** (Latin: *Vallum Antonini*) was a turf fortification on stone foundations, built by the Romans across what is now the Central Belt of Scotland, between the Firth of Clyde and the Firth of Forth.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Built some twenty years after Hadrian's Wall to the south, and intended to supersede it, while it was garrisoned it was the northernmost frontier barrier of the Roman Empire.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It spanned approximately 63 kilometres (39 miles) and was about 3 metres (10 feet) high and 5 metres (16 feet) wide.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Lidar scans have been carried out to establish the length of the wall and the Roman distance units used.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Security was bolstered by a deep ditch on the northern side.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It is thought that there was a wooden palisade on top of the turf.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The barrier was the second of two "great walls" created by the Romans in Great Britain in the second century AD.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Its ruins are less evident than those of the better-known and longer Hadrian's Wall to the south, primarily because the turf and wood wall has largely weathered away, unlike its stone-built southern predecessor.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Construction began in AD 142 at the order of Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Estimates of how long it took to complete vary widely, with six and twelve years most commonly proposed.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Antoninus Pius never visited Britain, unlike his predecessor Hadrian.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Pressure from the Caledonians probably led Antoninus to send the empire's troops farther north.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was protected by 16 forts with small fortlets between them; troop movement was facilitated by a road linking all the sites known as the Military Way.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The soldiers who built the wall commemorated the construction and their struggles with the Caledonians with decorative slabs, twenty of which survive.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned only eight years after completion, and the garrisons relocated rearward to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Most of the wall and its associated fortifications have been destroyed over time, but some remains are visible.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Many of these have come under the care of Historic Environment Scotland and the UNESCO World Heritage Committee.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius ordered the construction of the Antonine Wall around 142.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Quintus Lollius Urbicus, governor of Roman Britain at the time, initially supervised the effort, which may have taken as long as twelve years.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The wall stretches 63 kilometres (39 miles) from Old Kilpatrick in West Dunbartonshire on the Firth of Clyde to Carriden near Bo'ness on the Firth of Forth.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The wall was intended to extend Roman territory and dominance by replacing Hadrian's Wall 160 kilometres (100 miles) to the south, as the frontier of *Britannia*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] But while the Romans did establish forts and temporary camps further north of the Antonine Wall in order to protect their routes to northern Britain, they did not conquer the Caledonians, and the Antonine Wall suffered many attacks.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Romans called the land north of the wall *Caledonia*, though in some contexts the term may refer to the whole area north of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The land north of the Antonine Wall became known as Albany after the settlement of the Gaels in the 6th century.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was shorter than Hadrian's Wall and built of turf on a stone foundation, but it was still an impressive achievement.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It was also a simpler fortification than Hadrian's Wall insofar as it did not have a subsidiary ditch system (Vallum) behind it to the south.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] As built, the wall was typically a bank, about three metres (10 feet) high, made of layered turves and occasionally earth with a wide ditch on the north side, and a military way on the south.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The stone foundations and wing walls of the original forts on the Antonine Wall demonstrate that the original plan was to build a stone wall similar to Hadrian's Wall, but this was quickly amended.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Romans initially planned to build forts every 10 kilometres (6 miles), but this was soon revised to every 3.3 kilometres (2 miles), resulting in a total of nineteen forts along the wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The best preserved but also one of the smallest forts is Rough Castle Fort.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In addition to the forts, there are at least nine smaller fortlets, very likely on Roman mile spacings, which formed part of the original scheme, some of which were later replaced by forts.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The most visible fortlet is Kinneil, at the eastern end of the Wall, near Bo'ness.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] There was once a remarkable Roman structure within sight of the Antonine Wall at Stenhousemuir, which took its name from the Roman "stone house".
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] This was Arthur's O'on, a circular stone domed monument or rotunda, which might have been a temple, or a *tropaeum*, a victory monument.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It was demolished for its stone in 1743, though a replica exists at Penicuik House.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In addition to the line of the Wall itself there are a number of coastal forts both in the East (e.g.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Inveresk) and West (Outerwards and Lurg Moor), which should be considered as outposts and/or supply bases to the Wall itself.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In addition a number of forts further north were brought back into service in the Gask Ridge area, including Ardoch, Strageath, Bertha (Perth) and probably Dalginross and Cargill.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Recent research by Glasgow University has shown that the distance stones, stone sculptures unique to the Antonine Wall which were embedded in the wall to mark the lengths built by each legion, were brightly painted unlike their present bare appearance.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] These stones are preserved in the university's museum and are said to be the best-preserved examples of statuary from any Roman frontier.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Several of the slabs have been analysed by various techniques including portable X-ray fluorescence (pXRF).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Tiny remnants of paint have been detected by surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Several of the distance slabs have been scanned and 3-D videos produced.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] There are plans to reproduce the slabs, both digitally and in real physical copies, with their authentic colours.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] A copy of the Bridgeness Slab has already been made and can be found in Bo'ness.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It is also expected that lottery funding will allow replicas of distance markers to be placed along the length of the wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned within two decades of completion when the Roman legions withdrew to Hadrian's Wall in 162, and over time may have reached an accommodation with the Brythonic tribes of the area, whom they may have fostered as possible buffer states which would later become "The Old North".
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] After a series of attacks in 197, the emperor Septimius Severus arrived in Scotland in 208, and campaigned against the Maeatae (based in the central Midland Valley on either side of the Firth of Clyde – Firth of Forth line) and the Caledonians to their north.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] While he carried out substantial work on Hadrian's Wall at the time, there is no evidence of any attention being paid to the remains of the Antonine Wall during the campaigns of 208–210.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] References in Late Roman sources to Severus' wall-building activities led to later scholars like Bede mistaking references to the Antonine Wall for ones to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In the centuries that the Antonine Wall has lain abandoned, it has influenced culture between the Forth and the Clyde.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Bede associated Gildas's turf wall with the Antonine Wall.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Bede obviously identified Gildas's stone wall as Hadrian's Wall, but he sets its construction in the 5th century rather than the 120s, and does not mention Hadrian.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] And he would appear to have believed that the ditch-and-mound barrier known as the Vallum (just to the south of, and contemporary with, Hadrian's Wall) was the rampart constructed by Severus.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Many centuries would pass before just who built what became apparent.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In medieval histories, such as the chronicles of John of Fordun, the wall is called *Gryme's dyke*.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Fordun says that the name came from the grandfather of the imaginary king Eugenius son of Farquahar.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] This evolved over time into Graham's dyke – a name still found in Bo'ness at the wall's eastern end – and then linked with Clan Graham.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Of note is that Graeme in some parts of Scotland is a nickname for the devil, and Gryme's Dyke would thus be the Devil's Dyke, mirroring the name of the Roman limes in Southern Germany often called 'Teufelsmauer'.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Grímr and Grim are bynames for Odin or Wodan, who might be credited with the wish to build earthworks in unreasonably short periods of time.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] This name is the same one found as Grim's Ditch several times in England in connection with early ramparts: for example, near Wallingford, Oxfordshire or between Berkhamsted (Herts) and Bradenham (Bucks).
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Other names used by antiquarians include the Wall of Pius and the Antonine Vallum, after Antoninus Pius.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Edmund Spenser in Book II of *The Faerie Queene* (1590) alludes to the Wall, misattributing it to Constantine II.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Hector Boece in his 1527 *History of Scotland* called it the "wall of Abercorn", repeating the story that it had been destroyed by Graham.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Renaissance patrons in the 16th century, including George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal, who were exposed to the world of international scholarship through diplomacy, began to collect antiquities.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Earl Marischal set a stone from the Antonine Wall in the walls of Dunnotar Castle and had it painted and gilded, probably by Andrew Melville of Stonehaven.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The stone is now at the Hunterian Museum in Glasgow and residual paint traces probably remaining from its later reuse have been analysed.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The UK government's nomination of the Antonine Wall for World Heritage status to the international conservation body UNESCO was first officially announced in 2003.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It has been backed by the Scottish Government since 2005 and by Scotland's then Culture Minister Patricia Ferguson since 2006.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] It became the UK's official nomination in late January 2007, and MSPs were called to support the bid anew in May 2007.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was listed as an extension to the World Heritage Site "Frontiers of the Roman Empire" on 7 July 2008.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Though the Antonine Wall is mentioned in the text, it does not appear on UNESCO's map of world heritage properties.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Several individual sites along the line of the wall are in the care of Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] All sites are unmanned and open at all reasonable times.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The first capable effort to systematically map the Antonine Wall was undertaken in 1764 by William Roy, the forerunner of the Ordnance Survey.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] He provided accurate and detailed drawings of its remains, and where the wall has been destroyed by later development, his maps and drawings are now the only reliable record of it.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] In the 19th century, the Ordnance Survey showed the visible traces of the wall in some detail on its first- and second-edition maps at 25-inch and 6-inch scales, but no attempt was made then to undertake archaeological work.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Sir George Macdonald carried out systematic work on the wall that was published in 1911 and in an expanded second edition in 1934.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] His work provided the basis for a large-scale (25-inch) folio produced by the Ordnance Survey in 1931.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] The Ordnance Survey produced a revised folio in 1954–1957, and then carried out a new complete survey in 1979–80.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] They also published a smaller-scale map of the Wall, at 1:25,000 in 1969.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Further mapping activity was carried out to support the nomination of the Wall as a World Heritage Site.
[src:ala-roman-allied-military-unit/antonine-wall] Modern computer techniques like using GIS and LIDAR can now map the wall in three dimensions, making it much easier to study, for example, how visible forts and fortlets were to those at their neighbouring stations along the wall.
